50|$|Rawls derives two {{principles}} of justice {{from the original}} position. The first {{of these is the}} Liberty Principle, which establishes equal basic liberties for all citizens. 'Basic' liberty entails the (familiar in the liberal tradition) <b>freedoms</b> <b>of</b> <b>conscience,</b> association and expression as well as democratic rights; Rawls also includes a personal property right, but this is defended in terms of moral capacities and self-respect, rather than an appeal to a natural right of self-ownership (this distinguishes Rawls's account from the classical liberalism of John Locke and the libertarianism of Robert Nozick).|$|R
